33:57.637 --> 34:16.882
When

33:57.637 --> 34:16.882
we first arrived there, we had to undergo a test to 
convince the Army commander, Corps commander,

33:57.637 --> 34:16.882
that we were combat ready. So we had that, as soon as 
we arrived, a three-day exercise, which we passed

34:19.345 --> 34:26.614
with a high mark. And this was the first really test 
we had because the test we ran ourselves back in

34:27.252 --> 34:37.348
Fort Riley was not a three-day test. It was about a 
day and a half. So the only time we had that was

34:39.852 --> 34:44.800
necessary to complete our cycle for the BL. But we 
did very well on that test. And then we trained, of

34:47.904 --> 34:49.267
course. We had training airs in the barge around 
the train. And then we would go to I met, I don't know

34:57.037 --> 35:04.384
his name here, Kaiselard, a big German, was a 
German, training here, and then he was a Frenchman

34:57.037 --> 35:04.384
now. Trained there as a unit. And then once a year 
you have a training test for three days. Every

35:12.551 --> 35:14.553
month you have unannounced alerts.

35:19.497 --> 35:26.824
And those are good tests because then you can 
measure how quickly that you can assemble a unit,

