through that. Finally get it to the tall 
University of Kentucky that he had an overhead

36:59.289 --> 37:04.956
loop shot. As he fade away, you know. How did the 
American troops get along with the German

37:11.644 --> 37:15.148
civilians? Oh, now at this time, sure. Excellent. 
My wife Mimi was president of the German-American

37:20.896 --> 37:27.062
Women's Club. And of course she was president of 
ours also in the 18th Infantry.

37:33.308 --> 37:37.552
So we met, well she met with them, of course, but we 
had parties together. They had plans, social

37:37.613 --> 37:47.622
functions, charity things, which all here are 
very active. It was excellent. The press was good

37:49.752 --> 37:51.234
to us. We got good press, the German papers and 
Mannheim. And the

37:55.980 --> 38:01.566
troops got along well in the community. And by that 
time, sometimes there was resentment against the

38:03.589 --> 38:07.694
blacks. But by that time, they had certain taverns 
which were receptive to blacks. And these were the

38:15.924 --> 38:19.168
ones that you had a mixed marriage would go to those 
because the resentment wasn't so much against the

38:19.756 --> 38:28.825
black as it was against that blonde German girl 
from there in the black. They took the view of one of

38:28.845 --> 38:33.290
them, a real fine sergeant. We had a boxer. That's 
another 18th Infantry. We had champion boxers. I

38:38.816 --> 38:42.880
inherited those, but I took those over with us. So 
we had champions

38:44.161 --> 38:48.666
in the division. But they fought the Germans, too. 
